out 1374":"about 1374","1408":"1408","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Tarvin, Cheshire, England":"Tarvin, Cheshire, England","Bray, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, England","Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England":"Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England","England":"England","Yattendon, Berkshire, England":"Yattendon, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norreys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Norris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Norris","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Middle English <i>norreis</i>, <i>noreis</i>, <i>norais</i> ‘northerner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>noreis</i>), used both of Norwegians and of inhabitants of northern England and Scotland.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Norreis</i>, derived from <i>norreis</i> ‘northerner’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and 